{"id":5749,"date":"2015-05-05T07:00:59","date_gmt":"2015-05-05T13:00:59","guid":{"rendered":"http:\/\/www.succulentsandsunshine.com\/?p=5749"},"modified":"2018-12-08T13:49:40","modified_gmt":"2018-12-08T20:49:40","slug":"use-pot-feet-for-succulent-container-gardens","status":"publish","type":"post","link":"https:\/\/www.succulentsandsunshine.com\/use-pot-feet-for-succulent-container-gardens\/","title":{"rendered":"Use Pot Feet for Succulent Container Gardens"},"content":{"rendered":"<p><div class=\"fusion-fullwidth fullwidth-box fusion-builder-row-1 nonhundred-percent-fullwidth non-hundred-percent-height-scrolling\" style=\"background-color: rgba(255,255,255,0);background-position: center center;background-repeat: no-repeat;padding-top:0px;padding-right:0px;padding-bottom:0px;padding-left:0px;margin-bottom: 0px;margin-top: 0px;border-width: 0px 0px 0px 0px;border-color:#eae9e9;border-style:solid;\" ><div class=\"fusion-builder-row fusion-row\"><div class=\"fusion-layout-column fusion_builder_column fusion-builder-column-0 fusion_builder_column_1_1 1_1 fusion-one-full fusion-column-first fusion-column-last\" style=\"margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px;\"><div class=\"fusion-column-wrapper fusion-flex-column-wrapper-legacy\" style=\"background-position:left top;background-repeat:no-repeat;-webkit-background-size:cover;-moz-background-size:cover;-o-background-size:cover;background-size:cover;padding: 0px 0px 0px 0px;\"><div class=\"fusion-text fusion-text-1\"><p><em>If you haven't heard about pot feet, they just might be the best thing you can add to your succulent container gardens. Find out why they are so beneficial!<\/em><\/p>\n<p>My friend Laura Balaoro, a master gardener and fellow succulent lover, recently wrote a post about the importance of <a href=\"http:\/\/laurabalaoro.com\/why-it-use-pot-feet-in-containers\/\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener\">using pot feet<\/a> for container gardens. I hadn't heard pot feet mentioned anywhere else, but after seeing the rotted succulents in her pot without pot feet I knew this was something I needed to with my outdoor succulent containers.<\/p>\n<p><img class=\"alignnone wp-image-5763 size-full\" src=\"https:\/\/www.succulentsandsunshine.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2115\/05\/Learn-why-you-should-be-using-pot-feet-with-your-contanier-gardens.jpg\" alt=\"Learn why you should be using pot feet with your container gardens!\" width=\"735\" height=\"1102\" srcset=\"https:\/\/www.succulentsandsunshine.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2115\/05\/Learn-why-you-should-be-using-pot-feet-with-your-contanier-gardens-500x750.jpg 500w, https:\/\/www.succulentsandsunshine.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2115\/05\/Learn-why-you-should-be-using-pot-feet-with-your-contanier-gardens-700x1050.jpg 700w, https:\/\/www.succulentsandsunshine.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2115\/05\/Learn-why-you-should-be-using-pot-feet-with-your-contanier-gardens.jpg 735w\" sizes=\"(max-width: 735px) 100vw, 735px\" \/><\/p>\n<p>As you likely learned from <a href=\"http:\/\/laurabalaoro.com\/why-it-use-pot-feet-in-containers\/\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener\">Laura's blog post<\/a>, pot feet serve two major purposes. First off, they prevent your pot from staining the surface underneath them. I noticed some stains on my concrete last summer after moving some pots and it took months of rain and snow to get them off.<\/p>\n<p>Most importantly though, pot feet allow for air flow under the container which allows the soil to dry out completely between waterings. While you can control how much water your pot gets during the dry weeks, extended rain storms can easily fill a pot with water.<\/p>\n<p>Without pot feet there isn't space under the pot to allow the water to drain out more quickly. The air flow under the pot also helps the soil to dry out better.<\/p>\n<p><img class=\"alignnone wp-image-5764 size-full\" src=\"https:\/\/www.succulentsandsunshine.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2115\/05\/Learn-why-pot-feet-are-such-are-important-for-the-health-of-your-container-gardens.jpg\" alt=\"Learn why pot feet are such are important for the health of your container gardens!\" width=\"735\" height=\"1103\" srcset=\"https:\/\/www.succulentsandsunshine.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2115\/05\/Learn-why-pot-feet-are-such-are-important-for-the-health-of-your-container-gardens-500x750.jpg 500w, https:\/\/www.succulentsandsunshine.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2115\/05\/Learn-why-pot-feet-are-such-are-important-for-the-health-of-your-container-gardens-700x1050.jpg 700w, https:\/\/www.succulentsandsunshine.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2115\/05\/Learn-why-pot-feet-are-such-are-important-for-the-health-of-your-container-gardens.jpg 735w\" sizes=\"(max-width: 735px) 100vw, 735px\" \/><\/p>\n<p>I decided I needed to add pot feet under my pots of succulents. So, after doing some research, I decided to purchase a few different types of pot feet and see what I liked best. Here are the types I tried:<\/p>\n<ul>\n<li style=\"padding-left: 30px;\"><a href=\"https:\/\/www.amazon.com\/gp\/product\/B0006SQKDC\/ref=as_li_tl?ie=UTF8&camp=1789&creative=390957&creativeASIN=B0006SQKDC&linkCode=as2&tag=cassituttlpho-20&linkId=TB3ZIJS2HPO45XS2\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener nofollow sponsored\">Plantstand Pot Toes<\/a><\/li>\n<li style=\"padding-left: 30px;\"><a href=\"https:\/\/www.amazon.com\/gp\/product\/B003BNRBF0\/ref=as_li_tl?ie=UTF8&camp=1789&creative=390957&creativeASIN=B003BNRBF0&linkCode=as2&tag=cassituttlpho-20&linkId=DQZAWK2HVTDJWHMS\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener nofollow sponsored\">Pot Risers Invisible Pot Feet<\/a><\/li>\n<li style=\"padding-left: 30px;\"><a href=\"https:\/\/www.amazon.com\/gp\/product\/B0015QAZH6\/ref=as_li_tl?ie=UTF8&camp=1789&creative=390957&creativeASIN=B0015QAZH6&linkCode=as2&tag=cassituttlpho-20&linkId=5AOOGPB4UFEX3IA6\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener nofollow sponsored\">Cast Iron Plant Trolley<\/a><\/li>\n<\/ul>\n<p>Laura recommends using this <a href=\"https:\/\/www.amazon.com\/gp\/product\/B000OZROLO\/ref=as_li_tl?ie=UTF8&camp=1789&creative=390957&creativeASIN=B000OZROLO&linkCode=as2&tag=cassituttlpho-20&linkId=4N75W22UG53MZUJS\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener nofollow sponsored\">adjustable plant stand<\/a>.<\/p>\n<h3><a href=\"https:\/\/amzn.to\/1ZFGR3N\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener nofollow sponsored\">Click here to buy pot feet for your garden!<\/a><\/h3>\n<p>The great thing about the <a href=\"https:\/\/www.amazon.com\/gp\/product\/B0015QAZH6\/ref=as_li_tl?ie=UTF8&camp=1789&creative=390957&creativeASIN=B0015QAZH6&linkCode=as2&tag=cassituttlpho-20&linkId=5AOOGPB4UFEX3IA6\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener nofollow sponsored\">plant trolley<\/a> (also called a dolly or caddy) is it allows you to move the pot easily without lifting. I decided to place this one under a larger shallow pot I have.<\/p>\n<p>I've been indecisive about where to place this particular pot so I think the trolley is a great way to move it back and for until I commit. It is the most expensive option, but if you move your plants <a href=\"https:\/\/www.succulentsandsunshine.com\/caring-for-succulents-in-winter\/\">inside for the winter<\/a>, this makes that process much easier.<\/p>\n<p><img class=\"alignnone wp-image-5767 size-full\" src=\"https:\/\/www.succulentsandsunshine.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2115\/05\/Use-a-plant-dolly-to-move-heavy-containers.jpg\" alt=\"Use a plant dolly to move heavy containers\" width=\"735\" height=\"1103\" srcset=\"https:\/\/www.succulentsandsunshine.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2115\/05\/Use-a-plant-dolly-to-move-heavy-containers-500x750.jpg 500w, https:\/\/www.succulentsandsunshine.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2115\/05\/Use-a-plant-dolly-to-move-heavy-containers-700x1050.jpg 700w, https:\/\/www.succulentsandsunshine.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2115\/05\/Use-a-plant-dolly-to-move-heavy-containers.jpg 735w\" sizes=\"(max-width: 735px) 100vw, 735px\" \/><\/p>\n<p>I like the stability of the <a href=\"https:\/\/www.amazon.com\/gp\/product\/B0006SQKDC\/ref=as_li_tl?ie=UTF8&camp=1789&creative=390957&creativeASIN=B0006SQKDC&linkCode=as2&tag=cassituttlpho-20&linkId=TB3ZIJS2HPO45XS2\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener nofollow sponsored\">Pot Toes<\/a>, but they show quite a bit. I bought two colors and decided I liked the light grey because they blended in with the concrete better.<\/p>\n<p>With this pot I decided to just use 3 &#8220;toes&#8221; and it seems quite stable. They recommend using 3 or 4.<\/p>\n<p><img class=\"alignnone wp-image-5766 size-full\" src=\"https:\/\/www.succulentsandsunshine.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2115\/05\/Add-pot-feet-under-your-container-gardens-to-keep-them-healthy.jpg\" alt=\"Add pot feet under your container gardens to keep them healthy\" width=\"735\" height=\"490\" srcset=\"https:\/\/www.succulentsandsunshine.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2115\/05\/Add-pot-feet-under-your-container-gardens-to-keep-them-healthy-500x333.jpg 500w, https:\/\/www.succulentsandsunshine.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2115\/05\/Add-pot-feet-under-your-container-gardens-to-keep-them-healthy-700x467.jpg 700w, https:\/\/www.succulentsandsunshine.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2115\/05\/Add-pot-feet-under-your-container-gardens-to-keep-them-healthy.jpg 735w\" sizes=\"(max-width: 735px) 100vw, 735px\" \/><\/p>\n<p>The <a href=\"https:\/\/www.amazon.com\/gp\/product\/B003BNRBF0\/ref=as_li_tl?ie=UTF8&camp=1789&creative=390957&creativeASIN=B003BNRBF0&linkCode=as2&tag=cassituttlpho-20&linkId=DQZAWK2HVTDJWHMS\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener nofollow sponsored\">invisible feet<\/a> are my favorite. I like the fact that they are mostly &#8220;invisible&#8221;.<\/p>\n<p>While they do raise the container off the ground (which is the point of using them&#8230;) they don't show beyond that. Well, maybe if you're like me and you sometimes chase a baby on all fours you\u00a0<em>might<\/em>\u00a0be able to see them.<\/p>\n<p>I would definitely use 4 of these under each pot. 3 wasn't quite\u00a0stable enough, especially for this tall pot.<\/p>\n<p><img class=\"alignnone wp-image-5765 size-full\" src=\"https:\/\/www.succulentsandsunshine.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2115\/05\/Find-out-why-using-pot-feet-will-help-save-your-plants.jpg\" alt=\"Find out why using pot feet will help save your plants\" width=\"735\" height=\"490\" srcset=\"https:\/\/www.succulentsandsunshine.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2115\/05\/Find-out-why-using-pot-feet-will-help-save-your-plants-500x333.jpg 500w, https:\/\/www.succulentsandsunshine.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2115\/05\/Find-out-why-using-pot-feet-will-help-save-your-plants-700x467.jpg 700w, https:\/\/www.succulentsandsunshine.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2115\/05\/Find-out-why-using-pot-feet-will-help-save-your-plants.jpg 735w\" sizes=\"(max-width: 735px) 100vw, 735px\" \/><\/p>\n<p>I also have quite a few planters on a <a href=\"https:\/\/www.amazon.com\/gp\/product\/B004BDP674\/ref=as_li_tl?ie=UTF8&camp=1789&creative=390957&creativeASIN=B004BDP674&linkCode=as2&tag=cassituttlpho-20&linkId=XMDN6QK5T77PLYCK\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener nofollow sponsored\">wire rack<\/a>. This allows for excellent air circulation and there is plenty of room for the water to flow out. At the moment this isn't the prettiest part of my garden, but it is functional and should help prevent the plants in these pots from rotting!<\/p>\n<h3><a href=\"https:\/\/amzn.to\/1ZFGR3N\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener nofollow sponsored\">Click here to buy pot feet for your garden!<\/a><\/h3>\n<p>Ultimately, with any succulent container garden you need somewhere for the water to flow out easily and for air to circulate so the soil can dry out. I think pot feet might be the best tip I've received with succulent gardening this year, so thank you <a href=\"http:\/\/laurabalaoro.com\/why-it-use-pot-feet-in-containers\/\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener\">Laura<\/a>!<\/p>\n<p>What do you think about using pot feet? Is it something you already use in your garden or will be adding soon?<\/p>\n<\/div><div class=\"fusion-cl